    <message>
      <heading>Tue Feb  5 (Aidan)      :: Long Emote does not necessarily equal Good Emote</heading>
      <slot>5</slot>
      <level>199</level>
      <author>0</author>
      <date>0</date>
      <text>
I have seen a trend in the past couple of years for people to assume that
the longer emote is always the better emote. This has lead, in many cases,
to people adding tons of extra, unnecessary junk into their emotes to
satisfy some perverse word count. I am not saying that short emotes are
better. What I am saying is that -better- emotes are better. Quality stands
on its own and is not dictated by length. I will not be nearly as verbose
as I usually am and just include two quick examples. And yes, I am often
guilty of this padding of emotes, as well.

Short emote:
&amp;c
Joebob steps towards Jimbob and thrusts his sword towards his chest.
&amp;n
Long emote (with other &quot;frills&quot; that supposedly enhance one's RP):
&amp;C
Jo'eb'ob arches his left eyebrow, then his right, until they form an almost
perfect 'V' on his wrinkled and tanned brow. His blue eyes glare icy
daggers at Jimbob as he glides towards him thinking how easy it will be to
cut the other man to shreds with his vastly superior skill. Reaching back
over his shoulders, he draws the twin blades sheathed there, then does a
quick pirouette on his left foot, right foot snapping up to his hip to draw
the long knife from his belt sheathe. As his twirling motion brings him 
around to face his opponent once more, he slashes at him with all three
blades, the sunlight glinting off the higly polished metal reminding him of
the flaxen hair of his lover with whom he has a tryst planned beneath the
moonlit sky this very evening.
&amp;n
Which emote is better is left as an exercise for the reader. I was in a
hurry so I didn't take the time to add color to those words which, for
truly great RP, needed it, such as &quot;flaxen&quot; and &quot;moonlit&quot;. Oh, I think 
flaxen hair is blonde, but to be honest, I'm really not sure. It's one of
those two dollar words, so it's good even if it doesn't mean what I think
it does.

-Aidan
</text>
    </message>
